##Wuhan: A catering supply chain in a race against pneumonia

Micro-signal Zairenjian11

Features, with a calm narrative against the cold | phoenix network produced in the human studio

I am the author of the following article and the editor of the food channel of ifeng.com. On January 26, in addition to the New Year message, I was deeply moved by the pictures forwarded by a colleague. The colleague is from Wuhan, and she is as worried about her hometown and her family as many people in Wuhan who can not be reunited with their families.

So we decided to tell the heartwarming story behind this picture of her hometown, in this cold winter. Based on the photo information provided by this colleague, I interviewed the protagonist of the story, Ms. Qiu Beiwen. As the interview went on, I became good friends with several interviewees, and see the chivalrous tenderness behind this provincial capital, known as Wuhan.

One

At lunch on January 29, I explained the purpose of the interview to the interviewee, who sent a message: "I'm busy now, I'll get back to you later. "

30 minutes later, she called. There was a young voice on the other end of the line, urgent, not idle, and we made a tacit admission that it was going to be as if her name was Khubevan, born in the 90s..

At 4:47 a.m. on January 25, Qiu Beiwen, like tens of millions of people in Wuhan, lay awake in the worst affected part of the country. She finally made the difficult decision to call herself a friend, claiming that her restaurant could feed more medics in Wuhan.

In fact, from January 23, when the city was shut down in Wuhan, she had been delivering meals to several nearby hospitals for several days.

Qiu Beiwen and her husband run the restaurant "No. 8 warehouse" in the Huangpi District of Wuhan, near Wuhan Tianhe Airport. What used to be a seafood bbq restaurant has turned into a stir-fry and box-lunch during pneumonia. Even though the No. 8 warehouse is not close to the major hospitals in Wuhan where pneumonia patients are concentrated, Qiu Beiwen is determined to expand the distribution to the entire urban area of Wuhan.

I am the author of the following article and the editor of the food channel of ifeng.com. On January 26, in addition to the New Year message, I was deeply moved by the pictures forwarded by a colleague. The colleague is from Wuhan, and she is as worried about her hometown and her family as many people in Wuhan who can not be reunited with their families.

So we decided to tell the heartwarming story behind this picture of her hometown, in this cold winter. Based on the photo information provided by this colleague, I interviewed the protagonist of the story, Ms. Qiu Beiwen. As the interview went on, I became good friends with several interviewees, and see the chivalrous tenderness behind this provincial capital, known as Wuhan.

One

At lunch on January 29, I explained the purpose of the interview to the interviewee, who sent a message: "I'm busy now, I'll get back to you later. "

30 minutes later, she called. There was a young voice on the other end of the line, urgent, not idle, and we made a tacit admission that it was going to be as if her name was Khubevan, born in the 90s..

At 4:47 a.m. on January 25, Qiu Beiwen, like tens of millions of people in Wuhan, lay awake in the worst affected part of the country. She finally made the difficult decision to call herself a friend, claiming that her restaurant could feed more medics in Wuhan.

In fact, from January 23, when the city was shut down in Wuhan, she had been delivering meals to several nearby hospitals for several days.

Qiu Beiwen and her husband run the restaurant "No. 8 warehouse" in the Huangpi District of Wuhan, near Wuhan Tianhe Airport. What used to be a seafood bbq restaurant has turned into a stir-fry and box-lunch during pneumonia. Even though the No. 8 warehouse is not close to the major hospitals in Wuhan where pneumonia patients are concentrated, Qiu Beiwen is determined to expand the distribution to the entire urban area of Wuhan.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
"I also asked the staff for their opinion before the group was posted, and the staff were very supportive and willing to join, but when the group was posted, their families were very worried and wouldn't let them go anywhere. I can understand their families, however, and I am still grateful to the staff for their encouragement."Qiu Beiwen's circle of friends has been posted, the staff could not be there, and as the day grew brighter, he saw no hope of continuing the work.

Unexpectedly, her younger brothers and sisters volunteered to send out a request on Wechat to join, so that the manpower problem could be solved reluctantly, it has long been a necessary process in Wuhan for Qiu Beiwen to sterilize his car and his shop, inside and out.

"We charge, but we don't make any money, " she said, "originally we priced each meal at 8 yuan and 10 yuan, but now it's a problem to buy food all over Wuhan. Even the food we can buy is quite expensive, so we ended up with 15 yuan, two meat and one vegetable. We can't make money at this time, but I have to charge because we are a small business and the only way to help more people is to survive."

Qiu Beiwen's circle of friends landed on CCTV news. The first person to share the news was Qiu Beiwen's sister. The unanimous understanding and support of the comment area also increased Qiu Beiwen's determination to continue to do this, "anyone who knows the current situation in Wuhan knows that what I'm doing is very dangerous, " she said. "Life is always in front of us when the chips are down, money is behind us, and we really don't make any money. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
At this point in the interview, Qiu Beiwen on the other end of the phone has been steadfast, but when I asked Qiu Beiwen: "in the face of disaster, doctors are susceptible to people, when faced with them will you be afraid? " She froze for a moment, "I'm scared, even when I'm on the phone with you right now, my hands are shaking, " he admits

One of the most stressful aspects of the outbreak was Chiu Bevan -- a 28 year old mother of a child, with an elderly family to care for, mobilizing the whole family to do such a thing requires more responsibility than a single young person of her age.

"It is also because I have children that I want to do these things, because if the food of the first-line medical personnel who come to our Wuhan to support us can not be guaranteed, this epidemic will get worse and worse, " she said.

Qiu Beiwen and her husband have been in the catering business for some years. The family has a food delivery van and previously provided delivery services. Before the private car control was introduced in Wuhan on January 26, it was around this time that she and her siblings drove their own meals for the medical staff, and she felt the weight of life more intuitively.

She said most medical workers would let her leave her meals at the hospital entrance, and they would pick them up themselves, just to reduce contact with her. What impressed him most was a 23-year-old nurse sister. After she saw Qiu Beiwen, she beckoned to her from a distance and shouted, "sister, sister! " One second he was still frightened, and at that moment he gained courage.

Two

From January 26, motor vehicles will be banned in the central city of Wuhan. In addition to 6,000 taxis and 310 buses, only a few volunteer vehicles will be allowed to drive on the streets after applying. His private car is in a restricted area and volunteers have to take care of the transport and distribution of food.

Wang Chen, a native of Wuhan, 36, who runs an information technology company, died of illness two months ago. When he decided to volunteer, his father did not take a stand, but just said, "take care of yourself. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
In fact, Wang was more worried about his elderly father than he was about his own illness. Every time I went home, my father would greet me and inquire about the progress of my volunteer work, but every time he was stopped by Wang Chen: "Don't come over, go to the balcony and wait for me, wait for me to finish disinfecting! "

Wang said, because the city closed suddenly, medical staff traffic is the first thought, followed by the need for meals, so they formed a "team of volunteers" and "medical dining group. The volunteers in the group are made up of social caring people. All of them want to contribute their own strength when they encounter difficulties in Wuhan. Even if they can do little, it is good to do a little.

On New Year's Eve, Wang Chen and other volunteers stayed up all night, begin to organize teams spontaneously to assign tasks: VOLUNTEERS FORM A well-defined chain of execution starting with information matching, building platforms, fundraising, fund management, contact vehicles, hospitals, and catering.

Wang told me that there were two other doctors in the group who had been working on the front lines, not only to treat patients, but also to provide contact information for medical teams who needed transportation or meals.

"The first stage was information matching, when there was a lot of information on the Internet, and the original intention of US volunteers was to build a cluster platform where supply and demand could be precisely matched to address transportation and dining needs. On the day of the incident, many restaurant operators in their circle of friends were released spontaneously by them. They mainly contributed to the medical staff free of charge the food they had planned to use for the new year,"Wang said.

After collecting these scattered information, Wang Chen will check the network information of the supplier in the first place and screen out the true information. Wang said there are many more restaurants like No. 8 warehouse, but the main reason for choosing No. 8 warehouse is that it is located in Panlongcheng, in the Huangpi District District of Wuhan, and the food is relatively easier to buy than restaurants in the city, follow-up supplies will follow.

On the demand side, Wang is also responsible for collecting and sorting out the medical staff's needs for Chinese and dinner meals. After collecting information, he also carries out information matching to provide the most efficient supply plan.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
"The second stage is to solve the financial problem. When the catering companies could not continue to provide their services free of charge after the food and beverage inventory was depleted, we organized our friends to raise donations and continue to provide free supplies to the medical staff. There is a Certified Public Accountant in the group, and we ask them to account for every income and expenditure, and we support the restaurant business with the love of all sectors of society,"he said.

At its peak, Wang's team delivered more than 600 meals a day to hospitals, including the 672 hospital, the 5th Hospital, the Union Medical College Hospital and the Central General Hospital. The Fleet's caring owners transport medical staff hundreds of times a day.

When the demand was greatest, president Wu, the owner of the Wang Chunqiu catering company in Eastern Wu, reached out to volunteers and offered to cater for them regardless of cost. In addition, President Wu also undertook other large group meals, despite the shortage of raw materials, 200 meals were delivered to the hospital on January 28.

Wang Chen is part of a team that specializes in delivering food, he told me, "our other group, the ones that transport medical workers, deliver food when they're not busy, as if we were texting when we're done with the boxes, as if we had a free ride. ". We are very grateful to our excellent car owners in Wuhan for their hard work and regardless of cost."

Now, officials in Wuhan have advised that social vehicles should not be allowed to pass through, and that volunteer vehicles should be included as part of their protection. Officials provided a list of drivers and contact details, who were more well protected than Wang. Wang Chen also responded to the government's call in the first place and issued a public notice in all three groups.

"Now we still have some money left to spend, and we are thinking about contacting delivery platforms like Meituan to see how we can help the healthcare front line and achieve our original goal, " said Wang, who also asked for more advice from readers of the article.

When I asked Wang about more of their difficulties, Wang's optimism surprised me. "everything is starting to get better, but we still need time... " he said

Volunteers such as Wang were more susceptible to infection -- as if they had supported transport since the night of, when protection was inadequate and raincoats were used in the convoy. Faced with unknown diseases, they bear the burden of far more than normal people and fear. According to Wang Chen's words: "None of us is not afraid of. "

However, after the arrival of medical supplies, the weather gradually clearing up, the front-line volunteers to help transport medical staff began to receive medical staff to mask, disinfectant, alcohol and other supplies, which is to their surprise. At the time of delivery, medical staff packed up protective materials, put on thank-you notes, disinfected them and sent them to volunteers.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
This moment, he said, was like a ray of light breaking through the darkness.

Solving the problem of volunteer protection, another new problem emerged —— In the process of delivering food to medical staff, because the city could not find a restaurant, and the location of the No. 8 warehouse was relatively remote, the volunteers in the group need a long travel time because of the layers of control over the roads in the city. In addition to the limited food supply, there were times when there wasn't enough to go around and volunteers had to go to the convenience store to pick up pasta, sandwiches and snacks to make sure there was enough to go around.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Speaking of Qiu Beiwen and her No. 8 warehouse, Wang was very moved. He said Qiu Beiwen had been working spontaneously from beginning to end, sleeping only three or four hours a day. A small store provided nearly 600 meals for the hospital every day. He was also moved by the drivers who were very eager to help him pack his meals. In order to ensure that the meals were still warm in the hands of the medical staff, they even picked them up in batches, and then make a detour to get the food to the paramedics.

At the end of the interview, "We came up with a name for the team yesterday, " Wang told me with a smile. "It's called 'La a dream in Chu. ' The team has excellent practitioners from information-based enterprises, lawyers, media people, Certified Public Accountant, banking, communications, state-owned enterprises and many others who have not yet revealed their professional skills. However, we feel that this time we are all doing things like a robot cat, everything is OK, I hope we are the robot cat in Wuhan. "

Three

"SISTER, sister! " Classic of Poetry shouted into the face of the strange girl in the distance. She dared not come forward again, and only when she saw chiu leave could she summon her colleagues to bring hundreds of meals to the ward.

Classic of Poetry, 23, is a general nurse at a hospital in Wuhan. When I tried to get more specific information about her, she said: "I am just an ordinary medical staff, wearing this white clothes to have the courage to forge ahead, there are many medical staff like me. "

Asked any more questions, Classic of Poetry didn't respond, and I knew she was fighting a new battle. While the interview was on hold, I tried to get a sense of Classic of Poetry's recent work and life from her circle of friends.

Classic of Poetry's Hospital, a public hospital with a long history in the province, was not supposed to deal with infectious diseases, but during the outbreak, the hospital has also become one of the designated hospitals for pneumonia patients in the region. On New Year's Eve, Classic of Poetry Received The arrangement of hospital leadership, rushed to the hospital on the night shift.

If the National New Year's Eve this year than in previous years less lively, then for Wuhan to use the word "desolate" to describe it is not too much. Even so, Classic of Poetry donned a bright red coat, cut her hair short and plunged into intense therapy like a flower heroine -- as if it were a New Year's Eve in Wuhan.

In order not to delay the time of lesser, I arranged the problem to her in the form of Wechat, repeatedly said: "When you have time to return, send voice and so on. " When I returned the message, it was the next morning, "I'm sorry, I just got off the night shift, " Classic of Poetry said, before a series of Staccato voice messages. After hearing this, I began to be ashamed of my previous shallow understanding of the "hard work" of medical staff.

"We're working three shifts, six to eight hours each. The suits we wear are in short supply, expensive and expensive, so we wear them for six to eight hours or more. That way, from the moment we put on the suit, we can't eat, we can't drink, we can't go to the bathroom, so not only do we have to reduce water loss, but we also need diapers to help with our bowel movements. Of course, it's perfectly normal for health care workers not to eat on time,"Classic of Poetry said.

These needs, as volunteers Wang Chen and other caring people at the heart hospital looked into her eyes -- on January 28, 150 boxes of soft drinks, 200 boxes of bread, 50 boxes of diapers and 20 heating units arrived at Classic of Poetry's Hospital.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Classic of Poetry told me that for them, food and clothing is not the most difficult problem at the moment, but the most difficult problem is the shortage of medical supplies, such as surgical masks, N95 masks, protective clothing, isolation clothing, medical gloves... These are the materials they have to face directly with patients with pneumonia, if they do not have these things, they will face a great threat of infection. If even the medical staff is infected, the patient is less protected. So she also implore people from all walks of life through various channels to raise some reliable protective supplies.

When she saw Classic of Poetry, the 23-year-old girl gave her the courage, she said. I asked Classic of Poetry, "Are you afraid of the disease? "

"I'M NOT AFRAID! " She answered decisively, "As long as I'm in the door and wearing the suit, I'm not afraid. If I'm afraid, what about the patients, or the patients who haven't been diagnosed or are suspected of being diagnosed? "

"there is a lot of hope that we can feel it already, that some of the patients have been discharged safely, that some of the infected staff have been cured, that they are back in protective clothing and isolation, that they are on the front lines of fighting pneumonia -- as if it was courage for us, " she said

Through Classic of Poetry's Voice, I felt the power of what he said. I have not seen lesser, but no doubt through her voice delivered to me is a resolute eyes, a white dress by the 23-year-old girl's courage.

There are now more than 100,000 health care workers in Wuhan, like Classic of Poetry, who are either native to the city or from other provinces across the country. No matter where the spark came from, like the Hippocratic Oath or the nightingale oath they read upon graduation, those who stood in the middle of the storm felt more intuitively the full weight of life and death.

(with respect to the interviewees'wishes, Classic of Poetry was given an alias, and the rest of the names that appeared were real names.)
